preliminary

🛡️ National Security – Overview for UPSC
📌 Importance in UPSC Prelims:
Part of General Studies Paper I, under Current Events and Polity & Governance

Questions are mostly current-affairs based, related to national security institutions, threats, strategies, and international relations.

🔐 Key Areas Under National Security
1. Internal Security
Left Wing Extremism (LWE) – Naxalism

Terrorism (J&K issue, cross-border terrorism)

Insurgency in the Northeast

Communalism and religious violence

Cybersecurity threats

Radicalization and online extremism

2. External Security
Border management (India-China, India-Pakistan)

Maritime security (Indian Ocean, Navy presence)

Strategic ties (QUAD, Indo-Pacific)

Defense agreements and exercises (e.g., MALABAR, YUDH ABHYAS)

3. Security Forces and Agencies
Armed Forces (Army, Navy, Air Force)

CAPFs (CRPF, BSF, CISF, ITBP, SSB, Assam Rifles)

Intelligence agencies (RAW, IB, NIA)

NSG (National Security Guard), SPG, etc.

4. Cyber & Data Security
National Cyber Security Policy

CERT-In (Indian Computer Emergency Response Team)

Data protection issues (Personal Data Protection Bill)

Cyber warfare & cyber terrorism

5. Important Schemes & Frameworks
Modernisation of Police Forces (MPF)

National Intelligence Grid (NATGRID)

National Counter Terrorism Centre (NCTC)

Unlawful Activities Prevention Act (UAPA)

AFSPA – Armed Forces (Special Powers) Act

📚 Useful Sources for Preparation
PIB, PRS, and MHA annual reports

ARC Reports (especially 8th Report: “Combating Terrorism”)

IDSA & ORF websites (for analysis)

Newspaper editorials (The Hindu, Indian Express)

NCERTs (Polity & Geography), plus standard books like:

Challenges to Internal Security of India by Ashok Kumar IPS (for Mains + Prelims)

🧠 Sample Prelims Questions
Q: Which of the following organizations is primarily responsible for internal intelligence in India?
a) RAW
b) NIA
c) IB
d) NSG
Ans: c) IB

Q: Consider the following statements about NATGRID:

It is an intelligence sharing network.

It comes under the Ministry of Home Affairs.
Which is/are correct?
a) 1 only
b) 2 only
c) Both
d) Neither
Ans: c) Both



syllabus

1. UPSC Prelims Exam
Purpose: To screen candidates for the Mains exam.

Format:

2 Papers:

General Studies Paper I (200 marks)

CSAT (Civil Services Aptitude Test) Paper II (200 marks, qualifying)

Duration: Each paper is 2 hours.

Marking: Negative marking for wrong answers in Paper I.

Key Focus: Current affairs, basic general knowledge, and aptitude.

2. UPSC Mains Exam
Purpose: To test the candidate’s in-depth knowledge in various subjects.

Format:

9 papers in total:

Qualifying Papers (Indian Language & English)

Essays and General Studies (4 papers)

Optional Subject Papers (2 papers)

Total Marks: 1750 marks (for General Studies and Optional papers).

Key Focus: Descriptive writing, analytical skills, and subject knowledge.

3. UPSC Interview
Purpose: To assess personality, communication skills, and suitability for public service.

Format: Viva-voce (interview).

Marks: 275 marks.

Key Focus: Confidence, decision-making, and general awareness.

Summary:
Prelims: Objective test, to screen for the Mains.

Mains: Descriptive test, evaluates knowledge and writing skills.

Interview: Personal interaction, assesses overall personality.





🏁 STAGE 1: UPSC Preliminary Examination (Objective Type)
📘 General Studies Paper I (200 marks)
Current events of national and international importance

History of India and Indian National Movement

Indian and World Geography – Physical, Social, Economic Geography of India and the World

Indian Polity and Governance – Constitution, Political System, Panchayati Raj, Public Policy, Rights Issues, etc.

Economic and Social Development – Sustainable Development, Poverty, Inclusion, Demographics, Social Sector Initiatives

General issues on Environmental Ecology, Biodiversity and Climate Change

General Science

🧠 CSAT (General Studies Paper II – 200 marks, Qualifying, 33% marks needed)
Comprehension

Interpersonal skills including communication skills

Logical reasoning and analytical ability

Decision-making and problem-solving

General mental ability

Basic numeracy (Class X level)

Data interpretation (Class X level)

⏱️ Duration for Each Paper: 2 Hours
🚨 Note: Paper II is qualifying only. Marks of Paper I are counted for Prelims merit.

✍️ STAGE 2: UPSC Mains Examination (Descriptive Type)
Total of 9 papers: 2 qualifying + 7 merit papers
Total Marks (for ranking): 1750

📜 Qualifying Papers (300 marks each – need to pass, not counted in merit)
Paper A: Indian Language (from the 8th Schedule – e.g., Hindi, Tamil, Telugu, Bengali, etc.)

Paper B: English

📝 Papers Counted for Merit
🔹 Paper I: Essay (250 marks)
Write essays on multiple topics. Credit is given for effective expression, coherence, and relevance.

🔹 Paper II: General Studies I (250 marks)
Indian Heritage and Culture

History and Geography of the World and Society

🔹 Paper III: General Studies II (250 marks)
Governance, Constitution, Polity

Social Justice and International Relations

🔹 Paper IV: General Studies III (250 marks)
Technology

Economic Development

Biodiversity, Environment

Security and Disaster Management

🔹 Paper V: General Studies IV (250 marks)
Ethics, Integrity, and Aptitude

Case studies and theory-based questions on ethical issues

🔹 Papers VI & VII: Optional Subject (2 papers of 250 marks each)
Choose one subject (e.g., History, Geography, Sociology, PSIR, Anthropology, etc.)

Two papers based on chosen optional

🎤 STAGE 3: UPSC Personality Test / Interview (275 marks)
Face-to-face interview at UPSC Bhavan

Assesses personality traits, ethical values, communication, decision-making, leadership, etc.

No fixed syllabus – may include questions on:

Optional subject

Current affairs

Hobbies

Educational background

Situational judgment

🧾 Final Merit
Mains (1750) + Interview (275) = Total 2025 marks

📚 Top Resources for Syllabus Understanding
UPSC Notification PDF (on upsc.gov.in)

NCERT books (Class 6–12)

Standard books (Laxmikanth, Spectrum, GC Leong, Ramesh Singh, etc.)

Current affairs (The Hindu, PIB, Yojana, Kurukshetra)

Would you like this syllabus:

As a printable PDF

Formatted for a website page (HTML)

Divided into weekly study plans
Let me know and I’ll help you out!

